		<bioghist encodinganalog="MARC 545">
			<head altrender="biography" id="a2">BIOGRAPHICAL NOTE </head>
			<p>Cornell University Class of 1968. After graduating from Cornell, Deborah Rawson
				traveled to Japan, where she studied flower arranging and the tea ceremony. She
				returned to the U.S. to work on a master's degree from Hunter College and worked as
				a journalist for publications including Harper's Bazaar, "New York Talk," "On the
				Next Wave," and the Japanese edition of Cosmopolitan. In 1989, she published a book
				about her Vermont heritage, Without a Farmhouse Near. Deborah Rawson died in 1992. A
				room in the Carl A. Kroch Library is named in her memory.</p>
		</bioghist>
		<scopecontent encodinganalog="MARC 520">
			<head id="a3">COLLECTION DESCRIPTION</head>
			<p>Includes student notebooks and papers from grade school through college, photographs,
				letters to Rawson, subject files, and articles written by her.</p>
		</scopecontent>
